// Exponential Moving Average (EMA)
//
// EMA extends the simple moving average (SMA) by assigning exponentially
// decaying weights to past observations. Newer values receive higher weight
// through a decay parameter alpha, where 0 < alpha <= 1.
//
// The recursive definition is:
//   ema_t = alpha * x_t + (1 - alpha) * ema_{t-1}
//
// As a result, EMA is an autocorrelated time series and requires an initial
// seed value. Different seeding strategies lead to different early behavior.
//
// Relationship to SMA and time-series models:
//   - SMA is a finite-window MA(n) process.
//   - EMA corresponds to an infinite-memory AR(1)-type filter with decay
//     governed by alpha.
//
// Seeding options:
//   - seed_mode = 0: seed using SMA(n), with NA padding before index (n - 1).
//     This matches the default behavior of TTR::EMA.
//   - seed_mode = 1: seed using the first observation x[0], producing no
//     leading NA values.
//
// By default, technical analysis libraries use:
//   alpha = 2 / (n + 1)
// which is recommended for comparability with common TA tools.
//
// Alternative choices of alpha are also supported, including:
//   - Wilder’s smoothing: alpha = 1 / n (used for RSI, ATR, ADX)
//   - Half-life formulation: alpha = 1 - exp(-log(2) / half_life),
//     where half_life is a chosen number of steps for the EMA weight to decay by 50%
//   - Time-constant formulation: alpha = 1 - exp(-1 / tau),
//     where tau is a chosen continuous-time decay constant
//
// As with SMA, the EMA value at index i is defined only after x[i] is observed.
// The handling of early values depends on the chosen seeding strategy.

